value.name: HMS Devonshire (D02) - Wikipedia
value.snippet: HMS Devonshire was the first of the County-class destroyers and the first Batch 1 ship of the Royal Navy. The ship was built by Cammell Laird in Birkenhead near Liverpool. With a displacement of 5,440 tonnes (6,850 tonnes full load), Devonshire was named after the English county of Devon.

value.name: HMS Devonshire (39) - Wikipedia
value.snippet: HMS Devonshire, pennant number 39, was a County-class heavy cruiser of the London sub-class built for the Royal Navy in the late 1920s. The ship spent most of her pre- World War II career assigned to the Mediterranean Fleet aside from a brief tour with the China Station.

value.name: HMS «Devonshire» (1927) – Wikipedia
value.snippet: HMS «Devonshire» var en britisk krysser, kjent i Norge som skipet som evakuerte den norske regjeringen, kongen og kronprinsen i 1940. Hun begynte sin karriere med 1. krysserskvadron i Middelhavet og ble stort sett der frem til begynnelsen av den andre verdenskrig.

value.name: HMS Devonshire | James Bond Wiki | Fandom
value.snippet: HMS Devonshire was a British Royal Navy frigate under the command of Commander Richard Day. The ship was intentionally sent off-course into Chinese-held waters in the South China Sea by Henry Gupta using a stolen GPS encoder. This prompted two Chinese J-17 MiGs to investigate the frigate's unauthorised presence.

value.name: Devonshire - Global wiki. Wargaming.net
value.snippet: Devonshire carries a standard cruiser Damage Control Party , with a 5 second action time and a 60 second cooldown. She has the choice between mounting Defensive AA Fire or Hydroacoustic Search consumables. The Hydroacoustic Search is active for 100 seconds and will detect enemy ships at 4km and torpedoes at 3km.
